content: Welcome to the Online Renju Class theory lesson!

Now, we are ready to begin. Today we will see a very interesting D3 opening variant!
Many players like to use this 9th move. Why?
because black maybe not satified with other 9th moves
Yep, Because of, this K10 is a key point! On the other hand, it is good theory line for black :)
Another 9th move is F9, black gives up K10 and tries to surround white's stones and play positional move.
Of course, white takes key point at K10!
Two main black moves are possible here. Which two? Please answer!
H11 is GM's favorite, I guess :)
In former times H10 was more common. Nowdays H11 is applied often.
oh,dear lu, you come back so soon
Mainly, russian players prefer to use this H11 move. Eg. Viktor Barykin, Alexey Potapov etc...
Well, let's examine this H11 move. What is the difference between 11. H11 and 11. H10? Please explain your idea here!
black got two more active pairs while let 4-8 pair open
just try to break the silence =)
more active towards the left side
Others do not have any idea?
Let's see differences between two 11th moves:
What I think in mind has been told...

this is a space move, creates good base for attack
surrounds white's material, because of black forces white to play somewhere inside (G8, I10, G10 etc...)
if it is so good.....why h10 is still played
but white still possible to play outside like i12?
H10 is also not bad I think
i mean what makes h10 still a choice
that people dont know the idea behind h11 so well i guess
good suprise move, if your opponent do not know theory here, then she/he will be in trouble
that will be the topic of lessons about 9-h10, whywhy. So be patient:)
and the human feeling says: "it is aesthetic nice move" :-)))
I think in Renju, Go and other board games, the art and aesthetic feelings are also important when choosing good move,  no only calculating :-)
Here, there is well-known theory, with many analysis!
It is white advantage, or maybe sure win. I do not know correct evaluation.
maybe some other teachers will show in future theory lessons:)
:))) So this is the answer, whywhy
This 11th move defends white's pair 4_8 and surrounds white's material.
By the way..., Has black now VCT threat?
So the question is: if white passes her/his move, then can black win by VCT here? Please answer!
Yes, There is no black VCT here!
but white cannot pass its move
And here... Has black now VCT threat?
Black can win by VCT, so this 11th move is VCT threat move.
What are the possible white defences here? Please answer!
G8, G10, I10, I12, J11 and E8 are possible white defences.
But what about if white starts attack with 12.H10, 12.G11 or 12.K7?
Can white win in the right side?
No, so white need to defend in the left side, but black is enough strong to win the game.
This 16th is very strong defence, two 18th are possible: F8 and F10
Can you find it at home?
because of, white can take it earlier
Who would like to show win here? Please say me
Can you find the win at home from here?
White need to defend upper area

This 23 is VCT or VCF threat?
Let's see this move, this is the main 12th move!
Two black move are possible here. Which two moves?
Yes, I10 and G10. At present, I10 is used more frequently.
G12 is safe, K8 is sharp and risky.
15th is nice move, I think it is Alexey Potapov's analysis, but I am not sure.
Now white has a VCT threat upper side.
What is the next black move?
Two ways: 1. defend at J12 or 2. counterattack at F7
What is the meaning of the move F7? Please answer!
Two meanings: 1. it is a VCF threat 2. F7 controls white VCT at upper side
20th is a defence move, black 21th revives black VCF again, 22th is the only defence
Do nor worry, we will see that
I said, after 23th black has sure win
Let's check what will be happen if white will be active!
This 20th is cut move against black VCF threat.
What is the situation now? Please write here your explanation!
Black has very strong attacking area in the lower side! So white need to defend there.

E8 is the best, maybe no black win after 34. E8
